WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:21.380
All right. So my talk is focused on cilta cell efficacy, safety, and the questions we still need to answer. I think based on the data presented by Dr. Jaganath, Dr. Wuhi, and during ASCO, we are potentially witnessing the first curative therapy in multiple myeloma.

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:48.920
The word cure is pretty hard for me to say, but I'm learning to say it. But we still have many unanswered questions in terms of who are these patients that we're selecting, who will end up getting this cure, how do we prevent harm and decrease treatment-related mortality, and where it belongs in the treatment continuum as we get bispecifics and dual CAR-Ts and all these other novel agents that are in development.

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:51.480
All right. This is my talk.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:01:10.320
This is my disclosures. So these are the graphs for overall survival and progression-free survival from cilta cell, which was done in a heavily pre-treated patient population, overall response rates close to 97.9%, with stringency R rates of 82.5%, and a median survival of 60.7 months.

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:21.320
And one in three patients were disease-free, that means MRD-negative and PET-negative at five years in a patient population where overall survival...

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:23.320
And one in three patients were disease-free, that means MRD-negative and PET-negative at five years in a patient population where overall survival was roughly around 11 months.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:29.160
So that's a remarkable achievement that we've had based due to this therapy.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:33.120
And then, so how do we predict responders?

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:37.780
The biology of long responders, is it disease burden? Is it T-cell fitness?

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:47.260
Because if you can see on this table over here, when it comes to EMD, we always talk about EMD as a big risk factor for patients not doing well, not responding to therapy.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:51.480
And you can see over here that that number was comparable in both of these groups.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:02:07.180
The high tumor burden can go along with extramedullary disease, but that was much higher in 17.4% of the patients than the ones who had more than a five-year response.

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:10.520
And also, the T-cell fitness.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:17.360
So we noted that in the patients who were, the 33% of the patients, there was higher naive T-cell fraction in the drug product.

00:02:17.540 --> 00:02:19.380
There was lower tumor burden at baseline.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:21.280
There was higher effective to target.

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:27.780
Ratio when it comes to, and then also CD4 central memory CAR-T-cells were higher.

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:35.640
So ultimately, patients benefited regardless of high-risk cytogenetics or EMD, which is what we conventionally think of as when we stratify.

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:43.500
I mean, even now, when I have to decide a patient who's going to get first, second-line CAR-T, who are the patients I'm prioritizing?

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:46.420
The ones who have high-risk cytogenetics, the ones who have EMD.

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:50.940
But maybe we have to like twist it around and start thinking more about the T-cell biology.

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:51.480
But we have to think about the T-cell biology.

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.020
But we're not really there yet, and I think that's where our field has to go.

00:02:56.260 --> 00:03:17.320
And then, so we take from, we go from CAR T1 to CAR T4, and most of us are familiar with the trial schema, and you can oversee over here that, you know, CAR-T, in comparison to standard of care, which was PVD or DPD in this trial, you know, killed it in terms of their PFS, as well as their overall survival rates.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:21.460
And this was, this benefit was seen across a number of patients.

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:51.440
And this was, this benefit was seen across a number of patients.

00:03:51.440 --> 00:04:21.420
And this was, this benefit was seen across a number of patients.

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:22.860
And I think that's what we try to do.

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:26.440
That's the art of medicine, and that's what we strive to do every single day.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:37.640
So then we go to CAR T2, and, you know, many of us are familiar with the different cohorts where it was done in early relapse, patients who were functionally high-risk.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:44.060
But I think I want to pay attention to the cohort C, which is post-PCMA, right, whether they were bispecific or ADC-exposed.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:47.620
And you can see all the wonderful numbers that I showed you from CAR T1.

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:51.080
Those numbers over here don't really measure up.

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:54.540
We see a significant decline in terms of their PFS.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:05:02.860
And that's where the field is getting complicated, because we do have TECDARA and other bispecifics that are coming in earlier and earlier.

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:04.340
Okay.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:12.820
Real-world data where we have cilta-cel versus IDA-cel that was done, the work was done by the U.S. Myeloma Immunotherapy Consortium.

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:19.320
Dr. Hansen published, you know, cilta-cel efficacy higher, but then toxicity also higher.

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:20.820
And then...

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:39.160
Dr. Surbhi Sidhana published on the -- from the Immunotherapy Consortium, cilta-cel patients who were standard care cilta-cel with patients who had six prior lines of therapy, 54% of those patients would have not qualified for CAR T1, 14 had prior BCMA therapy.

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:46.440
And you saw that the patients had 89% overall response rate, but then there was a high percentage of patients who had non-conforming product.

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:50.980
And this may have been because this was early on in the era of commercial CAR-T launch.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:06:11.660
When there was a lot of wait time and delayed, you know, long manufacturing periods, but most recently, there was an abstract that was published at -- presented at Tandem that showed the significance of the -- I want to highlight that, that if patients did not respond to bridging therapy during their manufacturing time, the risk of Parkinsonism goes up 10 times higher.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:17.460
So that's something we have to keep in mind as we take patients to these therapies in the real world.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:17.700
And, of course, you know, CRS and ICANNs, which I think is one of the most important things that we need to keep in mind as we take patients to these therapies in the real world.

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:17.980
And, of course, you know, CRS and ICANNs, which I think is one of the most important things that we need to keep in mind as we take patients to these therapies in the real world.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:31.820
And, of course, you know, CRS and ICANNs, which I think is what the patients get worried about, but as a clinician who takes care of these patients, I'm not really worried about CRS and ICANNs because I think we -- the patients are in the hospital or in your outpatient program.

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:35.980
We -- by 10 years into CAR-T, we know how to manage CRS and ICANNs.

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:47.760
It's the HLH, it's the delayed -- it's the delayed neurotoxicities, whether it's Parkinsonism, how to detect it, you know, or the peripheral neuropathies and GBS, and now even IEC collagen.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.760
I don't think we have clear direction.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:55.760
All institutions are doing something different in terms of being mindful and picking these up.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:07:01.760
I think this is what is going to dictate how much cilta cell gets adopted and whether patients delay it.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.760
And second line from third line, I have 19 seconds, so I'll try to get through.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:12.760
And, of course, we've seen case reports that are published when it comes to actually CAR-positive T-cell lymphoma.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:17.540
All of them are in the New England Journal of Medicine, so I'm not going to go into the details.

00:07:17.540 --> 00:07:28.540
I'm not going to go into the details of that because that's beyond the scope of my talk, but you can see that, you know, this has been described not just with cilta cell, but also with other CAR products as well.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:47.320
And then, of course, I think today's dilemma is how does -- although we are saying we don't want to get patients -- we want to give CAR-T before bispecifics, that's what I feel as well, but I think as bispecifics will become readily available in the community,

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:55.320
so we're going to brace for a space where most of our patients will become BCM-exposed by the time we get them, and then we're going to learn how to take them to CAR-T.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:08:00.320
So on that note, my clinical conclusions, the cure conversation is real.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:05.320
It is no longer hypothetical, and nobody's going to tell you to get off the podium when you mention that word.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:09.320
The T-cell fitness predicts cure, not disease risk.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:15.320
I think there is an argument to move cilta cell earlier to give patients treatment independence time and time toxicity.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:17.100
I think CAR-T before BCMA bispecifics is a good idea.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:21.100
CAR-T before BCMA bispecifics makes sense, although accessibility for patients is a factor.

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:30.100
And, of course, delayed toxicities need structural surveillance programs, and the field is moving, and we have to embrace what is to come and when it's going to be dual and triple target CAR Ts.

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:32.100
On that note, I am done.
